Any single second of time can be represented as a 32-bit unsigned integer in a Unix-compatible system. 
Fetching the value for the current time is done by calling the 'time()' function: 

		push dword 0 		; Push a 32-bit null pointer to stack, since 
					; we don't need a buffer. Time value is
					; returned in eax. 
		call time		; Returns calendar time in eax 
		add esp, byte 4		; Stack cleanup for 1 parm 
		mov [oldtime], eax	; Save time value in memory variable 

The 'time()' function can potentially return the 'time_t' value in two places: 
		
		1) EAX 
		2) A buffer that you allocate somewhere. 
To have 'time()' place value in a buffer, you pass it a pointer to the buffer on the stack. 
If you don't want to store the time calue in a buffer, then you must still hand it a null pointer on the stack. 
That's why we push a 0 value in the preceding code; 0 is the value of a null pointer. 
No other parameters need to be passed to 'time()'. 
On return, you'll have the current 'time_t' value in EAX. 

